### What makes the parsing actually correct here

The parser is a **character-by-character state machine** — no regex hacks, no `split(',')` nonsense:

| Case | How it's handled |
|---|---|
| `"field with, comma"` | Enters quoted mode on `"`, reads everything literally until the closing `"` |
| `""escaped quote""` | Inside a quoted field, `""` is consumed as a single `"` character |
| `"multi\nline"` | Newlines inside quoted fields are treated as literal characters, not row breaks |
| Unquoted fields | Read until delimiter or newline, no special processing needed |
| Mixed rows | Each field is evaluated independently — quoted and unquoted can coexist |
| Empty fields | `,,` or a trailing delimiter correctly produces empty string fields |

